2. PROBLEM STATEMENT & SCIENTIFIC MOTIVATION 
2.1 The Challenge: ISRO's Exact Words 
"I have Chandrayaan-2 radar and imagery data. I need to find subsurface ice, select a 
landing site, plan a rover route, and estimate ice volume." 
— BAH 2026 Challenge #8, ISRO Session 1 Problem Statement 
2.2 Why Lunar South Polar Ice Matters 
Water-ice at the lunar south pole is the single most strategically valuable resource for India's future deep
space programme. If accessible in recoverable quantities, it can be electrolysed into liquid hydrogen (LH₂) 
and liquid oxygen (LOX) rocket propellant — enabling a Moon-based refuelling depot that dramatically 
reduces the cost of cislunar and Mars missions. It can also supply potable water and provide radiation 
shielding for crewed outposts. India's LUPEX mission (jointly with JAXA) and Chandrayaan-4 both 
critically require accurate subsurface ice maps — with precise landing coordinates and access routes — 
to select viable drilling and sampling sites. DIPSAR provides exactly this. 
2.3 The Scientific Breakthrough — ISRO's Own 2026 Paper 
The scientific foundation of Challenge #8 was laid by a landmark paper published on 6 May 2026 in npj 
Space Exploration by ISRO scientists at the Physical Research Laboratory, Ahmedabad: Sinha, R.K., 
Bharti, R.R., Acharyya, K., Mishra, S.K., Srivastava, N., & Bhardwaj, A. (2026). 'Subsurface ice in doubly 
shadowed craters as revealed by Chandrayaan-2 dual frequency synthetic aperture radar.' npj Space 
Exploration, 2, Article 22. 
This paper analyzed nine Doubly Permanently Shadowed Region (DPSR) craters within Faustini, 
Haworth, and Shoemaker using DFSAR L- and S-band full-polarimetric data. Its key findings — which 
our pipeline directly implements — are: 
