• Doubly shadowed craters reach interior temperatures of ~25 K (the coldest places in the inner 
solar system), making them the highest-priority targets for long-term stable subsurface ice 
preservation. 
• Four craters — F2 (Faustini), F3 (Faustini), H3 (Haworth), S1 (Shoemaker) — show elevated 
CPR > 1 with DOP < 0.13, establishing a refined criterion for subsurface ice via volumetric 
scattering. 
• Crater F2 (87.39°S, 82.31°E, diameter ~1.1 km) shows the strongest evidence: CPR up to 1.95, 
47% of interior pixels with elevated CPR, DOP of 0.10–0.13, AND a prominent lobate-rim 
morphology — indicating excavation into subsurface ice. 
• The dual criterion CPR > 1 AND DOP < 0.13 definitively separates volumetric scattering from ice 
vs. surface roughness false-positives (high CPR but DOP > 0.35), resolving the longstanding 
ambiguity in radar-based lunar ice detection. 
 
