Why Crater F2 is Our Primary Target 
Crater F2 within Faustini PSR is the single highest-priority excavation target in the lunar south polar 
region. It has the highest CPR (1.95), the largest fraction of ice-positive pixels (47%), DOP of 0.10 — the 
lowest of all studied craters — AND the unique lobate-rim morphology that Sinha et al. (2026) interpret 
as direct physical evidence of impact excavation into subsurface ice. Its impact point at −2744 m elevation 
is ~180 m below the surrounding Faustini floor, indicating penetration into a deeper, colder, ice-rich 
stratum. This is our primary rover excavation destination. 
 
