6 Ice Volume 
Estimation 
For each ice-positive pixel in each crater: 
compute L-band penetration depth δ = 
λ/(4π×Im(√ε)), where λ=0.24m (L-band), 
ε_ice=3.15+0.001j → δ ≈ 1.0–2.5 m. 
Estimate ice fraction per pixel from CPR 
magnitude above threshold: f_ice = (CPR 
− 1.0) / (CPR_max − 1.0) × f_max (f_max 
~ 0.3 as conservative estimate). Compute 
pixel ice volume: V_pixel = pixel_area × δ 
× f_ice. Sum across all ice-positive pixels 
per crater. Convert to mass: M = V × ρ_ice 
(917 kg/m³). Output: ice mass table per 
crater (tonnes) with depth-band breakdown 
(0–1m, 1–3m, 3–5m). 
numpy: vectorized volume 
computation across all 
pixels. pandas: crater-level 
aggregation. Plotly: bar chart 
of ice mass per crater per 
depth band. 
 
4.1 The Refined Ice Detection Criterion — ISRO's Own Science 
The detection criterion we implement is the one established and validated by ISRO's own scientists in 
Sinha et al. (2026). This is critically important — our results will be directly comparable to ISRO's 
published baseline, giving judges a clear validation benchmark: 
CPR > 1 AND DOP < 0.13 CPR > 1 but DOP > 0.35 CPR < 1 and DOP > 0.2 
✓ SUBSURFACE ICE: 
Volumetric scattering from ice 
deposits. Strong evidence of 
water-ice at depth. 
✗ FALSE POSITIVE: Surface 
roughness (rocky terrain, 
impact melt flows, blocky 
ejecta). NOT ice. 
○ DRY REGOLITH: Normal 
lunar surface. No ice. Double
bounce or specular scattering. 
 
