Investigating the distribution and stability of water-ice at the lunar poles has
long been a key scientificpriority1–13, particularly for assessing in situ
resources essential for supporting future crewed lunar missions and
outposts14–16. Among the coldest environments on the Moon1–13, doubly
shadowed craters represent a special class of craters located within larger
permanently shadowed regions at the lunar poles17–19. The raised rim of the
doubly shadowed crater provides effective double shielding of the crater
interior from scattered light and thermal emission from nearby sunlit
surfaces17–19. Because of this double shielding, thermal modeling predicts
that the floors of these craters can reach extremely low temperatures of ~25
K17–19 and are thus high priority targets for hosting stable subsurface water
ice deposits in their interior18.
